@flexiarg writing-coherence/unearned-essentially
@title Replace the Rhetorical Collapse With the Structural Reason
@keywords essentially, fundamentally, simply, basically, rhetorical-work, load-bearing
@audience paper authors, reviewers
@tone technical
@style pattern
@references [writing-coherence/subheading-without-paragraph writing-coherence/hedged-lift]

! conclusion: Words like "essentially", "fundamentally", "simply", "basically", "just" ask the reader to accept that the current sentence is the collapsed form of a deeper argument.  They do rhetorical work the paper has not done.  Either the actual structural reason belongs in the sentence — at which point the adverb is redundant — or no collapse has been earned — at which point the adverb lies.
  + context: These adverbs are one of the clearest AI-prose signatures.  They compress without doing the work of compression.  Used well, "essentially" signals that a careful argument has been made earlier and is now being invoked; used badly, it signals that the writer wishes the argument had been made.
  + TENSION:
    Axis: rhetorical force ↔ argumentative warrant.
    Real: a genuine "essentially" is efficient — it lets a reader skip the full derivation when they already have it.  A counterfeit "essentially" extracts the efficiency without paying for it.
    Irreducible: the same adverb cannot simultaneously earn its collapse (reader has the derivation) and substitute for the derivation (reader does not).
    Active: the pull recurs whenever a claim needs to sound harder-earned than the paper has actually earned.
  + COMPOSITIONS:
    (1) Replace with the structural reason: if the adverb is load-bearing, state the reason it compresses.  "Essentially multiplicative" becomes "multiplicative because D and A combine as a product, so either dimension alone can bound the whole" — and the adverb is redundant.
    (2) Cut the adverb: if the reader already has the derivation from earlier in the paper, the collapse is earned and the adverb is decorative.  Remove it.
    (3) Earn the collapse: if the adverb is load-bearing and the derivation has not appeared, write the derivation (possibly in a prior paragraph or footnote) before invoking the collapse.
  + CHECK:
    Engaged when: every instance of "essentially / fundamentally / simply / basically / just" in the draft either has a prior derivation the reader can point to, or is explicitly replaced by the structural reason, or is cut.  Failing when: the adverb is the strongest warrant the claim has.
  + FAILURE-MODES:
    - Essentially as warrant: "the relationship is essentially X" where X is the actual structural claim being made for the first time.
    - Simply as softener: "the argument is simply that..." where the argument is, in fact, not simple.
    - Fundamentally as gravitas: "fundamentally, this is about..." where the adverb adds weight but no information.
    - Just as scope control: "we just need to show that..." where the claim being shown is actually substantial.
